\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Eddie stepped off the ferry first, tossing a few coins to the ferryman before offering a hand to Torrie. As her boots hit the wooden planks, she immediately turned to take in their surroundings, but Eddie tugged his flat cap lower over his forehead, his gaze flickering warily over the busy dock.}
\par\plain {The air here was different\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 crisper, drier. It lacked the thick, briny scent of Weshaven, replaced instead by the rich aromas of spice crates being unloaded, the earthy tang of dried herbs, and the occasional whiff of parchment and ink from merchants tallying their stock.}
\par\plain {Osthaven was busier in a different way. Where Weshaven had the steady rhythm of fishermen mending nets and gutting the morning\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s catch, Osthaven hummed with the brisk efficiency of trade. Dockhands hauled crates marked with foreign sigils, couriers weaved through carts, and merchants haggled over silk and spices from distant lands.}
\par\plain {Torrie took it all in, wide-eyed. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s\u8230\'85 bigger than I thought.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie forced a smirk. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Told you. Less fish guts, more commerce.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {But even as he spoke, his steps were measured, his shoulders tense beneath his coat. He pulled his flat cap down further, a quiet gesture of habit\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 of avoidance of the last time he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d walked these streets.}
\par\plain {He tried not to think about it. Tried not to wonder if someone in the crowd might recognize him, might turn and whisper. It had been a year, but memories had a way of lingering.}
\par\plain {Torrie, oblivious to his unease, strode ahead, drinking in every detail.}
\par\plain {"Look at that!" she pointed excitedly to a trio of scholars in deep blue robes, their arms laden with books as they argued in hushed, hurried tones. "Are they from the university?"}
\par\plain {"Yeah," Eddie muttered. "Researchers, probably. Aella\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s got plenty of them."}
\par\plain {They continued down the road, weaving through colorful stalls and past warehouse workers shouting orders.}
\par\plain {Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s gaze landed on a small stall by the corner, where the scent of roasted chestnuts drifted through the air. His fingers brushed against the strap of his bag as a familiar memory surfaced.}
\par\plain {"See that?" He nudged Torrie. "Markus and I used to stop there after classes. We\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d split a bag of chestnuts and complain about assignments the whole way home."}
\par\plain {Torrie wrinkled her nose. "You two really bonded over complaining, huh?"}
\par\plain {Eddie smirked. "It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s an art form, I tell you."}
\par\plain {But the warmth of nostalgia faded too quickly, replaced by the weight pressing at his ribs. He shouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t be here. Not for long.}
\par\plain {As they walked past a faded green awning, his steps faltered.}
\par\plain {"And that place," he pointed, voice quieter now, "was where I used to get supplies for my\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 projects."}
\par\plain {Torrie arched a brow. "What kind of }{\f0\fs24\i1 projects}{?"}
\par\plain {"Alchemy, mostly," Eddie said, exhaling softly. "The owner\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 grumpiest old man you'd ever meet\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 used to grumble about every single request I made, but he never actually turned me away."}
\par\plain {Torrie grinned. "Sounds like he liked you."}
\par\plain {Eddie scoffed. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I think he just liked my coins.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {The humor felt thin, fleeting. His fingers curled slightly, pressing into his palms. It was strange, being back. The streets hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t changed, but everything }{\f0\fs24\i1 felt}{ different.}
\par\plain {Torrie, still beaming, nudged him lightly. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ve been here a lot, huh?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie hesitated before nodding. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yeah\u8230\'85 long ago.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well,\u8221\'94 Torrie said, her voice light, \u8220\'93now I\u8217\'92m here too.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie huffed a quiet laugh, shaking his head as if to brush away the past. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yeah. Let\u8217\'92s get you to Aella.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {He didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t look back.}
