\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Eddie pedaled through the last stretch of road, the cobbled streets of Osthaven giving way to packed dirt as they left the bustle of town behind. Fields of golden hay swayed gently in the morning breeze, stretching far and wide, their soft rustling the only sound accompanying them now.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And then, past the gentle slope of the hill, Aella Academy came into view.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It stood just as Eddie remembered\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 tall, sturdy, with its weathered stone walls and a modest courtyard nestled at its center. It wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t the grandest school in Solivia, not the kind spoken of in hushed reverence like Edenfield, but around here, it was everything. A place of learning, discipline, and quiet ambition.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Eddie slowed the bike to a stop near the front gate. Torrie hopped off, adjusting her satchel, her eyes gleaming as she took in the sight before her.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well,\u8221\'94 she said, turning to him, a wide grin breaking across her face, \u8220\'93I guess this is it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0  \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ll do fine, Torrie.\u8221\'94 Eddie said, forcing a small smirk. \u8220\'93You better not cause too much trouble.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 She stuck her tongue out playfully before stepping forward, her pace quickening until she was practically skipping through the front gate.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Eddie lingered by the entrance, watching her go. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He saw himself in her.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The same eagerness, the same restless energy that had carried him through these very gates years ago. He remembered what it was like, standing on the threshold of something new, looking ahead and seeing only possibility.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Now, he stood on the other side of it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Eddie let out a quiet breath, gripping the handles a little tighter before shaking his head.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Go get \u8216\'91em, Torrie.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And with that, he turned the bike around and started pedaling back towards town.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {He just had to get back to town, maybe find a quiet corner to sit for a while before catching the ferry home. But as he was about to mount his bike, a voice cut through the crowds of students.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Edward!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {He flinched. His fingers tightened around the handlebars. For a second, he considered pretending he hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t heard. Plenty of students had the name Edward, right? It didn\u8217\'92t have to be him.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\i1 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Edward!\u8230\'85 Welton!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie slowed, his stomach knotting. Slowly, hesitantly, he turned his head.}
\par\plain {Near the front gate of Aella Academy, amidst the stream of students hurrying into the school, stood Mr. Ferie. Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s old Alchemy mentor was just as he remembered\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 dark-skinned, balding, his round brass glasses perched on his nose, and an ever-present spark of energy in his step despite his age. The students passing by greeted him with cheerful nods and waves, a testament to how well-liked he was. And then, as he spotted Eddie, his face lit up with recognition, his hoarse but warm voice cutting through the morning air.}
\par\plain {Mr. Ferie strode toward him, clapping a firm hand on his shoulder. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Hah! I thought that was you! It\u8217\'92s been years! How have you been, my boy?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie swallowed, forcing his lips into something that resembled a smile. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Uh\u8230\'85 yeah. It\u8217\'92s been a while.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Mr. Ferie beamed. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93More than a while! I haven\u8217\'92t seen you since\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94 He paused, brow furrowing slightly as he searched for the last memory he had of Eddie. Then, his face brightened again. \u8220\'93Ah, since that competition! You had the judges hanging onto your every word\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Professor Borman from Edenfield even wrote you a recommendation, didn\u8217\'92t he?\u8221\'94 He chuckled, adjusting his brass-rimmed glasses. \u8220\'93So? Did you take the chance? Studying Alchemy at Edenfield, I hope?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie felt something sour coil in his stomach. He gripped the strap of his bag a little tighter.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Something like that.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Mr. Ferie chuckled. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ah, I knew it. You always had a mind for it, Edward. All those competitions\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 still remember the time you turned an iron ingot into living vinework? That was a masterpiece! One of the finest young alchemists I ever had the pleasure of mentoring.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie stiffened. He could feel the expectation in Mr. Ferie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s voice, the unshaken belief in who he used to be.}
\par\plain {His hands felt clammy. The last thing he wanted was to stand here, listening to praise that didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t belong to him anymore.}
\par\plain {Mr. Ferie, oblivious to his unease, clapped his hands together. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So! What brings you back to Osthaven? Surely not just a visit?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie shifted his weight. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Just dropping someone off.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh? A friend?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93My\u8230\'85 sister.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Mr. Ferie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s brows lifted. \u8220\'93Torrie, was it? Following in your footsteps, then! That\u8217\'92s wonderful.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie forced a chuckle, but it barely held.}
\par\plain {Mr. Ferie sighed wistfully. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ah, you know, I always hoped I\u8217\'92d see you again, Edward. You had such promise. I can only imagine the things you\u8217\'92ve accomplished since Edenfield.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s throat tightened. He glanced away, fingers gripping the strap of his bag as if it could anchor him. His mind scrambled for an exit.}
\par\plain {Lie. Tell him you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re doing fine. That you\u8217\'92re excelling. That you\u8217\'92re still the student he remembers.}
\par\plain {But the words wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t come.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 uh, I should get going,\u8221\'94 Eddie blurted. \u8220\'93Mum\u8217\'92s expecting me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Mr. Ferie blinked, surprise flickering across his face. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh? Well, I suppose we\u8217\'92ll catch up properly another time\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {But Eddie was already moving, swinging himself onto his bike. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yeah\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 yeah, of course,\u8221\'94 he called over his shoulder, forcing a smile that didn\u8217\'92t quite reach his eyes.}
\par\plain {And then he was pedaling away, fast enough that the cobbled road rattled beneath his tires. Fast enough that Mr. Ferie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s voice faded into the morning hum of Aella Academy. Fast enough that he didn\u8217\'92t have to see the warmth in his mentor\u8217\'92s eyes turn into something else\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 realization, maybe, or disappointment.}
\par\plain {He didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t look back.}
